 they had seventeen documented children between then and approximately 1788. Edward Hooker's 1909 genealogy entries 1022-1037 list the children — though crowdsourced records add and subtract from this number in places."},{"number":2,"category":"military","header":"Revolutionary War private from West Hartford","body":"He mustered as a private in the Revolutionary War from West Hartford — alongside thousands of other Connecticut farmers and tradesmen who left family homesteads for the Continental ranks. He survived the war and returned to West Hartford where he lived another three decades."},{"number":3,"category":"death","header":"Widowed twelve years before his 1814 death","body":"His wife Abigail Hooker died at West Hartford on 8 August 1802 after thirty-nine years of marriage. He lived twelve more years alone at West Hartford before his own death on 17 March 1814 at age sixty-nine."}],"cross_connections":[],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM113","plot":"Row 13","plot_notes":"Old Center Cemetery, West Hartford CT. Buried in row 13 (per Findagrave + WikiTree)."},"military_service":[{"war":"American Revolutionary War","service_years":"1776","rank":"Private","unit":"4th Company, Connecticut Troops, under Lieut. Charles Seymour","role":"Soldier","notes":"Enlisted Aug 15, 1776 in the 4th Company, Connecticut Troops under Lieut. Charles Seymour. Marched toward New York Aug 16, 1776 — set sail from New Haven and arrived in New York. Date of discharge not known. Sources: Connecticut Rolls and Lists Vol XIII p.234; West Hartford Church Records; West Hartford Cemetery Records p.41.","war_id":"WAR004"}],"bio":{"title":"Pvt.","first_name":"Henry","last_name":"Brace","married_names":[],"suffix":"III","display_name":"Pvt. Henry Brace III"},"number_of_marriages":1,"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"slug":"henry-brace-iii-1744"},"H00396":{"id":"H00396","ha